fdød","1375–Male":"1375–Afdød","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1493":"1493","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","Abt 1430":"omkring 1430","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Otterton, Devonshire, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"nl":{"1412–1456":"1412–1456","1414–1432":"1414–1432","1426–1493":"1426–1493","1430–Female":"1430–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1493":"1493","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","Abt 1430":"circa 1430","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Otterton, Devonshire, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1412–1456":"1412–1456","1414–1432":"1414–1432","1426–1493":"1426–1493","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1493":"1493","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","Abt 1430":"about 1430","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Otterton, Devonshire, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Layton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Slayton","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Leighton   (compare   Layton  ) with the addition of initial <i>S-</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Sladen   or of <b>Sleightholme</b>, principally a habitational name from Sleightholme Dale in Kirkbymoorside, but perhaps occasionally from Sleightholme in Bowes or the lost Sleightholme in Lythe. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>sléttr</i> ‘smooth, level’ + <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is now very rare in Britain. Compare   Slaydon  ."]},{"name":"Leaton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Letton","meanings":["English: habitational name, most probably from Letton in Norfolk or Latton in Essex. It could also be a variant of   Leighton   or   Laughton  . Most of the places so named have the same etymology as Letton and Latton, i.e. ‘farm where leeks are grown’ (Old English <i>lēac-tūn</i>). Another possibility is that it is a variant of   Latten  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":43,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Leighton was born in 1412, in Leighton, Shropshire, England, his father, Thomas Leighton, was 37 and his mother, Margareta Drake, was 23. He married Joan Joyce Cornwall in 1429. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1456, in Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, at the age of 44, and was buried in Leighton, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"1412–1456":"1412–1456","1414–1432":"1414–1432","1426–1493":"1426–1493","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1493":"1493","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1414":"1414","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","Otterton, Devonshire, England":"Otterton, Devon, England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1412–1456":"1412–1456","1414–1432":"1414–1432","1426–1493":"1426–1493","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1493":"1493","1390":"1390